```

What do you mean by failed here? Cause it can fail in two ways, if the initial endpoint rejects the request or if the mina node ends up rejecting it due to transaction logic. 

For the first case, I believe `.send` will throw an error if the endpoint fails.

For the second case, you can call `.wait` and it can eventually fail as well. Something like 

```ts
   let pendingTransaction = txn.send();
   if (pendingTransaction.status === 'pending') {
     console.log('Transaction accepted for processing by the Mina daemon.');
     try {
       await pendingTransaction.wait();
       console.log('Transaction successfully included in a block.');
     } catch (error) {
       console.error('Transaction was rejected or failed to be included in a block:', error);
     }
   } else {
     console.error('Transaction was not accepted for processing by the Mina daemon.');
   }
```

Does that work for your use case?

This is how I tried to convert a recent transaction hash to base64:

```ts
import { Bytes, fetchTransactionStatus } from 'o1js';
import baseX from 'base-x';
const BASE58_ALPHABET = '123456789ABCDEFGHJKLMNPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijkmnopqrstuvwxyz';
const base58 = baseX(BASE58_ALPHABET);

const byteArray = base58.decode('5Ju5wFBxRtGRB194e4HaEJ9DuLjTrmq5XkqXKHcZ2zQ5tRGhpQ8W');
const bytes = Bytes.from(byteArray);
const encodedBytes = bytes.base64Encode();
const decoder = new TextDecoder('utf-8');
const str = decoder.decode(new Uint8Array(encodedBytes.bytes.map(b => b.toNumber())));
console.log(str);

const status = await fetchTransactionStatus(str, 'https://api.minascan.io/node/devnet/v1/graphql');
console.log(status);
```

